# Agent memory

Use the `memory` CLI only

## Session start

**First action every chat:** run `memory` in the shell. It resolves scope from the workspace cwd and prints local plus global entries.

## When to read again

Run `memory` before similar work, when you hit a recurring issue, or when the user asks what has been learned. Use `memory view <id>` for one entry, or `memory -g` for global only.

## When to add

Add only when the lesson would save time next session:

- Recurring pitfall or non-obvious convention
- Fix that took real investigation

Skip one-off task notes, obvious facts, or topics already covered. Run `memory` first - duplicate ids are rejected.

## How to add

```bash
memory add <kebab-id> "<one sentence, max 120 chars>"
memory add <kebab-id> "<one sentence>" --detail "<root cause, fix, why it wasn't obvious>"
memory add -g <kebab-id> "<sentence>"   # global.json
```

- `<kebab-id>`: lowercase letters, digits, hyphens only
- Sentence: single line, 120 chars max. Quote it if the shell would split it
- Use `--detail` for anything that does not fit in the one-liner
- Default scope: `repos/<repo>.json` under `~/git/<repo>/...`, else `misc/<path>.json` (`home` for `~`, `dotfiles` for `~/dotfiles`, etc.)

### Examples

```bash
# Good: non-obvious, reusable
memory add stow-symlink "dotfiles stow skips targets that already exist as real files"

# Skip: one-off, no cross-session value
memory add fixed-typo "fixed a typo in README"
```
